265	Margaret 	Fuller	1810	1850	www.margaretfuller.wordpress.com	265	Sarah Margaret Fuller was born in Cambridgeport, Massachusetts, the first child of Margarett Crane Fuller and Timothy Fuller.  Desiring a son, her Harvard-educated lawyer/politician father gave her a classical male education. Margaret was pushed to the limits, which produced recurring headaches and nightmares. Her only solace was sitting in her mothers luscious flower garden.\n\nAt 21 years old, Margaret experienced a spiritual crisis during a Unitarian church service which heralded an epiphany that led her toward the intuitive knowing of the emerging Transcendentalist movement. Her father retired from his four-term political service in the U.S. House of Representatives to become a farmer in Groton, Massachusetts. In 1835, he died unexpectedly of cholera. As the eldest son, Margaret was obligated to go out and work for her mother and younger siblings, whom she also taught. She gave up her dream of going on the Grand Tour of Europe.\n\nMargaret met Transcendentalist Ralph Waldo Emerson and taught for A. Bronson Alcott, father of Louisa May Alcott, at his experimental Temple School in Boston. She was invited to be a member of the Transcendental Club, where she was treated by the men as an equal. During 1839, Margaret published her translation of Eckermanns Conversation with Goethe, became the first editor of the Transcendentalist Dial magazine, and began her first series of Conversations for women in Boston. \n\nElizabeth Cady Stanton and Mrs. Horace Greeley attended some of her Conversations. Margaret published The Great Lawsuit: Man vs. Men, Woman vs. Women, in the Dial in 1843. She traveled with companions through the West, which was the Great Lakes region then, and wrote about this sojourn in her book, Summer on the Lakes, researching as the first woman allowed in Harvard library. Horace Greeley, publisher of the New York Tribune, became so enamored of the West Margaret described in her book, coupled with his wifes insistence, that he hired Margaret as the first woman reporter.\n\nOn her way from Boston to New York City in the fall of 1844, Margaret spent seven weeks in Fishkill Landing, NY, revising The Great Lawsuit into the first American feminist book, Woman in the Nineteenth Century. Published in 1845 by Greeley, the book became a national and international bestseller. From 1844 to 1846, Margaret wrote social and literary criticism, exposing the corruption in hospitals and prisons while defining and supporting the new American literature. Considered the most brilliant woman in America, she was met only by Edgar Allan Poe as an outstanding literary critic.\n\nHer friends, Rebecca and Marcus Spring, offered Margaret the Grand Tour of Europe in 1846. She negotiated with Greeley to become his first woman foreign correspondent. Margaret travelled through England, Scotland, and France, meeting Italian revolutionary exile, Giuseppe Mazzini, Polish poet exile, Adam Mickiewicz, and her mentor, writer George Sand, and Sands lover, pianist Frederic Chopin. She awakened to the peoples unrest and discontent and wrote about their struggles.\n\nDuring Holy Week in St. Peters Basilica, Vatican City, Margaret met Count Giovanni Angelo Ossoli, whom she came back to be with in Rome after she became ill on the Grand Tour in 1847. Margaret gave birth to Angelo Eugenio Filippo Ossoli in Rieti, Italy, on September 5, 1848. During the Roman Revolution, she remained the only American in Rome, serving the wounded and dying Roman soldiers as director of the field hospital on the Tiber.  Her husband fought for the peoples Revolution. \n\nCatholic France bombarded Rome while Margaret wrote of the horror as first woman war correspondent. With Romes fall, Margaret and Ossoli escaped to Florence where she continued to write her firsthand account of the Roman Revolution. They met Elizabeth Barrett Browning and Robert Browning there. Returning to America to start afresh in New York Citys Italian community, Margaret, Ossoli, and their child, Angelino, perished in a shipwreck during a hurricane off Fire Island, New York on July 19, 1850.  From Margaret Fuller: Transcendentalist, First Woman Reporter, and Revolutionary\nBy Michael Barnett, M.Div., M. Ed., Margaret Fuller Scholar, Theologian, and Educator\n    \n\n	2016-08-25 17:40:14.774783	\N	f	t	1	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/34/Margaret_Fuller_by_Chappel.jpg	
