351	Rabba Sara	Hurwitz	1977			351	Rabba Sara Hurwitz has modestly risen into a leading role in the Orthodox Judiasm, which is a first for a woman. Rabba Sara Hurwitz was born in 1977 in apartheid-era South Africa. Hurwitz and her family immigrated to the U. S. in 1989 when her parents became more and more disillusioned by the political oppression in their country. Moving from a very insular and quiet community in South Africa to a diverse and hectic Florida neighborhood was challenging. However, Hurwitz found great joy in the communal life of her synagogue, which helped her transition. In 2009, having mastered all the texts required of male rabbinical students, this love of being at her synagogue evolved into a calling when Hurwitz became the 1st woman in the U. S. publicly ordained as an Orthodox rabbi. Though her conferring ceremony was met with some furor, it was also met with tremendous interest from Orthodox women who wanted to serve their communities. As a result, Hurwitz and her mentor, Rabbi Avi Weiss, began a school for women who wanted to pursue rabbinical studies  the Yeshivat Maharat. Six years later, Hurwitz dream of no longer being the only rabba in the Orthodox Jewish community seems to be closer to becoming a reality. In 2013, the Yeshivat Maharats inaugural class included 3 graduates, all of whom immediately found employment in synagogues and schools.\n\nIn speaking of her school, Rabba Hurwitz stated: I dreamt a dream, and it has surpassed my expectations  Yeshivat Maharat is no longer a dream. It is an unassailable part of the Jewish landscape. Chalom Chalamti. I dreamt a dream, and it became a reality because of the many students, supporters, and advocates, who shared the dream for an Orthodox community where men and women can lead as full members of the clergy.	2016-08-25 17:40:16.062811	\N	f	t	1	https://www.facebook.com/nycrecords/photos/a.147315912073130.30085.127234500747938/632317156906334/?type=3	
353	Anne	Hutchinson	1591	1643	https://www.womenofthehall.org/	353	She was a woman of haughty and fierce carriage, a nimble wit and active spirit, a very voluble tongue, more bold than a man, said Governor John Winthrop of religious pioneer Anne Hutchinson, whom he expelled from the Massachusetts Bay Colony in 1638 for her insistence on practicing religion as she chose, and on preaching herself.\nAn immigrant from England who settled in the New World in 1634, Anne Hutchinson (1591-1643) came under fire from the colony elders when she began expounding her theology at meetings in her home. She believed in a covenant of grace, in which faith alone was enough to achieve salvation. Others disagreed, and when Winthrop became governor, Hutchinson was banished and excommunicated. She moved with her family to the area of the country that became Rhode Island, and after her husbands death, she moved to Long Island, where in 1643 she and five of her six children were killed in an Indian attack. This advocate of freedom of religion, the right to free assembly and womens rights was honored in the naming of the Hutchinson River and the Hutchinson River Parkway.\n\n	2016-08-25 17:40:16.093265	\N	f	t	1	https://www.womenofthehall.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/anne-hutchinson-150x150.jpg	
