352	Anne	Hutchinson	1591	1643	tobyzliederman@gmail.com                                                                                                                              	352	Anne Marbury Hutchinson was born in Elizabethan England. From her mother, Bridget Dryden Marbury, she learned the skills she would use all her life - midwifery, healing and herbalism. From her minister father, Francis Marbury, she received a solid theological education, as well as an understanding of the meaning of religious dissent. In 1612, she and William Hutchinson, a prosperous merchant from their Alford hometown, married. With their eleven children, they left England in 1634 to follow early Puritan leader and minister John Cotton to the new colony in Boston, Massachusetts.\n\nIn addition to her many household duties, Anne was healer for the sick and midwife to her child-bearing neighbors. Writings differ regarding the womens study group she began and its size, possibly eighty or more. Men sometimes joined in, and concerns about fair business practices and religious intolerance probably were discussed. Leaders became worried.\n\nIn our countrys early history, church and state were one, with many of the same men functioning as leaders of both. Although her husband and many others supported her medical and religious activities, her views and popularity were likely too much of a threat to the all-male leaders of the colony. Forty-six years old and pregnant, she was charged as a heretic and brought before the Massachusetts General Court in November, 1637. For two days she defended herself skillfully, matching her extensive knowledge against Governor John Winthrop and her other accusers. Winthrops detailed records state that her meetings were intolerable, nor fitting for your sex.\n\nHutchinson was not only tried before the General Court, but also faced a second trial by the church. In neither trial was she allowed any defense witnesses! Even so, she might have been freed for lack of just cause and conflicting testimony, except that when she claimed she had received direct revelations from God, her accusers had their out. How dare anyone but clergy make such a claim, let alone a woman! Not only did the civil court order her banished, but she was also excommunicated in 1638.\n\nThe Hutchinsons, along with some of their family and followers, travelled to the new and tolerant colony of Rhode Island. There they founded the settlement we know as Portsmouth. While there are no documentson record,  its assumed that William died in 1642. Still threatened by Massachusetts leaders, Anne and her party of sixteen moved once more. They settled in the northeast section of present-day Bronx/Lower Westchester, where the parkway and river that bear her name are located. \n\nHer death was likely the result of Dutch land takeovers and conflicting land claims between Governor Kieft and the Native Americans. Because of his brutality to them, she--who practiced racial tolerance and refused to keep firearms--and all but one daughter were murdered in what was probably a retaliatory attack against Kieft in August, 1643.\n\nShe has made her place in history/herstory, an early example of many of our rights today: our right to dissent, freedom of assembly, free speech, religious freedom and tolerance, womens rights, and separation of religion and government. She had the courage and strength to stand up for her beliefs, even when personal consequences were drastic. Indeed, many consider her Americas first feminist.\n\nAdapted from papers by Sharon Mills, Eleanor Rae and Toby Z. Liederman, with editing assistance from Annette Sambolin. \n\n	2016-08-25 17:40:16.076102	\N	f	t	1	https://media1.britannica.com/eb-media/29/164529-004-8F2776F0.jpg	
357	Shirley Ann 	Jackson	1949		https://www.womenofthehall.org/	357	Dr. Shirley Ann Jackson, a visionary scientist, educator and public policy innovator, has broken barriers and blazed trails throughout her life.\nDr. Jackson was one of the first two African-American women to receive a doctorate in physics in the United States and was the first African-American woman to receive a doctorate from Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Committed to promoting social justice, she organized MITs Black Student Union and worked to increase the number of blacks entering MIT. After only one year, the number entering rose from 2 to 57.\nA renowned physicist, Dr. Jackson was appointed Chairman of the United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) in 1995 by President Clinton. While there, she enhanced the commissions regulatory effectiveness and initiated a bottom-up strategic assessment of all NRC activities. As the first African American woman to serve on the NRC and the first woman and African American to lead the entity, Dr. Jackson reaffirmed that agencys commitment to public health and safety.\nIn 1999, Dr. Jackson became the 18th President of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, the oldest technological university in the United States, and has led an extraordinary transformation of the school since her arrival through an ambitious strategic initiative known as The Rensselaer Plan.\nDr. Jacksons numerous awards and wide-ranging work demonstrate the capability of women and minorities to join the leadership ranks in science and technology, education and public policy. A 2007 recipient of the prestigious Vannevar Bush Award for a lifetime of achievements in scientific research, education, and senior statesman-like contributions to public policy, Dr. Jackson holds 45 honorary doctoral degrees and is the recipient of countless other awards.\nTime Magazine quite aptly described Dr. Jackson in 2005 as perhaps the ultimate role model for women in science.\n        \n	2016-08-25 17