492	Belle 	Moskowitz	1877	1933		492	Belle Moskowitz, a central figure in Democratic Governor Alfred E. Smiths kitchen cabinet, was born in Harlem, N. Y., the daughter East Prussian immigrants.  After attending city schools and (for a year) Teachers College at Columbia University, in 1900 she became a settlement worker at the Educational Alliance, a Jewish settlement on New Yorks Lower East Side.  In 1903, she married Charles Henry Israels, an architect, with whom she raised three children.  She did editorial work for the social reform journal The Survey and volunteered for charitable organizations, focusing on recreational resources for urban working girls.  In 1908, she launched a successful drive to license New Yorks commercial dance halls. \n\nCharles Israels died of heart disease in 1911.  To support her children, Belle wrote a pamphlet on child care (The Child) for the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company and worked as Commercial Recreation Secretary for the Playground and Recreation Association.  In January 1913 she became grievance clerk for the Dress and Waist Manufacturers Association, which fired her in 1916 for being too pro-labor.  \n\nIn 1914, Belle married Henry Moskowitz, a settlement worker, industrial mediator, and then president of the citys Civil Service Commission.  She opened a public relations firm and worked for woman suffrage.  In 1918, she organized the womans vote for Al Smiths campaign for governor and soon was advising him on policy issues.  As Publicity Director for the State Democratic Committee, she counseled Smith on public relations, wrote his speeches, prepared and monitored legislation, and identified appointees for strategic posts.  When in 1926 his fourth gubernatorial victory expanded his national profile, she coordinated a network of supporters that led to Smiths national Democratic Party nomination in 1928.\n\nDuring this race, as the only woman on the executive committee of the Democratic National Committee, Moskowitz directed the campaigns publicity.  After his loss to Herbert Hoover, she stayed on as Smiths press agent, trying (in vain) to retain his party leadership.  In 1932 Franklin Delano Roosevelt defeated Smith for the Democratic nomination and won the presidency.  In December, Moskowitz fell down the steps of her upper West Side brownstone, while recovering from broken bones suffered an embolism, and died.\n\nThe era of Smiths ascendancy in the national Democratic party was one when women, unless related by blood or marriage to political figures, never achieved such proximity to power.  Moskowitz succeeded by offering Smith a total and selfless loyalty, a strategy that had consequences for Moskowitzs place in history.  When his career declines, so did hers.  As a result, she remained a generally forgotten figure until the modern womens history movement revived awareness of her extraordinary career.\n\nElisabeth Israels Perry\nBIBLIOGRAPHICAL NOTE\n\nMoskowitzs papers, mostly of a private nature and saved only from the last few years of her life, are at Connecticut College in New London, Conn.  The only complete biography is Elisabeth Israels Perry, Belle Moskowitz: Feminine Politics and the Exercise of Power in the Age of Alfred E. Smith (1987).  For related material, see Mary R. Beard, Womans Work in Municipalities (1915); David Burner, The Politics of Provincialism: The Democratic Party in Transition, 1918 1932 (1975); Robert Caro, The Power Broker. Robert Moses and the Fall of New York (1974); Paula Eldot, Governor Alfred E. Smith, The Politician As Reformer (1983); Matthew and Hannah Josephson, Al Smith: Hero of the Cities. A Political Portrait Drawing on the Papers of Frances Perkins (1969); and Robert A. Slayton, Empire Statesman: The Rise and Redemption of Al Smith (N.Y.: Free Press, 2001).\n	2016-08-25 17:40:18.490093	\N	f	t	1	http://jwa.org/sites/jwa.org/files/styles/default_full/public/mediaobjects/Moskowitz-Belle.jpg?itok=lqIbuh2M	
493	Constance Baker 	Motley	1921	2005	https://www.womenofthehall.org/	493	Making history and making law are the twin components of Constance Baker Motleys extraordinary life and career. Motleys legal career began as a law clerk in the fledgling National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Legal Defense and Education Fund, where she clerked for Thurgood Marshall.\nShe became a key legal strategist in the civil rights movement, helping to desegregate Southern schools, busses, lunch counters  and successfully argued nine of ten cases before the U.S. Supreme Court.\nIn 1964, Motley became the first African-American woman elected to the New York State Senate; in 1965 she was chosen Manhattan Borough President  the first woman and first African-American in that position; and in 1966, President Lyndon Johnson named her a Federal Court judge  the first African-American woman so named. Known as an incisive and capable judge, Motley believes her presence makes a difference: As the first black and first woman, I am proving in everything I do that blacks and women are as capable as anyone.\n	2016-08-25 17:40:18.508849	\N	f	t	1	https://www.womenofthehall.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/constance-baker-motley-150x150.jpg	
494	Lucretia	Mott	1793	1880	https://www.womenofthehall.org/	494	The daughter of a sea captain, Lucretia Coffin spent her childhood on Nantucket Island. She was reared in the Quaker faith, unique among American religions in encouraging the equality of women.\nIn 1811 she married James Mott and they made their home in Philadelphia. Soon she began to speak in Quaker meetings, developing confidence and eloquence that were rare at a time when women seldom spoke in public.\nIn the 1830s Mott advocated the radical idea that slavery was sinful and must be abolished. She was one of several American delegates to the 1840 Worlds Anti-Slavery Convention in London, but the women were denied seats. There she bonded with Elizabeth Cady Stanton whose husband was a delegate. The lesson was clear for Mott and Stanton. How could women fight for the rights of others unless they enjoyed rights of their own?\nIn 1848, while Mott was visiting her sister in Auburn, New York, she met with Stanton and helped to plan the first womans rights convention. Mott delivered the opening and closing addresses at the Seneca Falls Convention, and her husband James chaired the proceedings at the Wesleyan Chapel.\nMotivated by her religious convictions, Mott dedicated herself to the twin causes of antislavery and womens rights. She harbored runaways slaves in her Philadelphia home and agitated for Negro suffrage and education when emancipation was finally won. As she wrote, spoke, and attended womens conventions, younger feminists recognized that Motts early leadership had been crucial in the infancy of the womens rights movement.\n	2016-08-25 17:40:18.527717	\N	f	t	1	https://www.womenofthehall.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/lucretia-mott-150x150.jpg	
