1270	Clare	Hollingworth	1911	2017	http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/10/clare-hollingworth-dies-aged-105-telegraph-correspondent-broke/	1214	Clare Hollingworth was a pioneer and a British war correspondent. Hollingworth was the woman who broke the news that World War II had started and alerted the British embassy in Warsaw which they doubted her and she held out the telephone outside the window for them to hear the sound and they found her report accurate. Hollingworth was born in Knighton in 1911. She studied at the University of Zagreb and then to Yugoslavia. After college she started actively in politics and an intelligent in Warsaw. Hollingworth started helping thousands of refugees from the Sudetenland that had been annexed by the Nazis. Hollingworth helped them with travel documents and secured their safety traveled into Poland. In 1939, less than a week on her first job as a reporter for the British Daily Telegraph newspaper, she was praised after she reported spotting German tanks on the Polish border and her article published the next day. They called it the, scoop of the century. Through her years as a reporter, (to The Telegraph, The Guardian, The International Herald Tribune, and the Wall Street Journal) she reported conflicts throughout Africa, Europe, and Asia. In 1941, Hollingworth was the first to interview the 21 year old Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who became the shah of Iran (overthrown by revolutionaries in 1979). In 1946, Hollingworth was in Jerusalem when the hotel she stayed at was bombed by Zionist paramilitaries. In 1972, she became the Telegraphs first Beijing correspondent since 1949. She was in China and reported back on the Cultural Revolution (violence and civil war that took hundreds of thousands of life). In 1997, Hollingworth traveled to Hong Kong to report on the Colonys handover to China. She later became an institution there, joining the citys Foreign Correspondents Club. Hollingworth covered the civil war in Pakistan, India and Vietnam. Hollingworth saved many lives during the Nazis control in WWII. She was one of the best known scoops of the century in the Journalism world. Hollingworth sealed the gaps for women in journalism and her legacy is capture by so many. She was awarded the What The Papers Say lifetime achievement award. Hollingworth was made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire by Queen Elizabeth II. Hollingworth passed away in Hong Kong at the age of 105.	2017-01-24 20:45:54.036332	\N	f	t	1	https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/01/11/business/11hollingworth-obit-2/11hollingworth-obit-2-blog427.jpg	\N
757	Anna Wessels 	Williams	1863	1954		757	Anna Wessels Williams is an American bacteriologist who graduated from New Jersey State Normal School in 1883 and the New York Infirmary Woman's Medical College, MD in 1891.\nWilliams was a scientist who made possible the widespread, cost-effective production of diphtheria antitoxin and also aided in the diagnosis of rabies. Together with William Hallock Park, she produced successful antitoxin for diphtheria (1894) and also produced a method of determining presence of rabies in pathology (1896). Anna served as assistant director of the New York City Research Laboratories (19051934).  She wrote numerous medical papers, articles, and textbooks, including (as co-author) Pathogenic Microorganisms Including Bacteria and Protozoa (1905) and Who's Who among the Microbes (1929). Anna was the first women to be elected to the laboratory section of American Public Health Association.\n	2016-08-25 17:40:22.948657	\N	f	t	1	https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/img/portraits/331.jpg	
