1135	Ana 	Sandoval			www.globalfundforwomen.org	1087	Working In: Guatemala\r\nOrganization: Peaceful Resistance La Puya\r\nDEFENDING: Community rights to land and resources and demanding the closure of the Progreso VII mine\r\n\r\nIn the end, all the struggles have the same objective: the defense of life. That is the most important, no matter where we are or what the specific goal of each fight is.\r\nAna Sandoval\r\n\r\nAna Sandoval hadnt yet finished high school when she began asking the questions that would lead her to co-found Communities in Peaceful Resistance La Puya to oppose a gold mining megaproject in her community. She soon became a leader of an unprecedented movement to defend land and resources, based on non-violent direct action and led by women.\r\n\r\nAs a student, Ana began to investigate the mining projects around La Cholea, her hometown in Guatemala. Despite the governments denials, she discovered that mining concessions had been granted for vast areas in the San Jose del Golfo and San Pedro Ayampuc municipalities. Ana and other residents feared the environmental disaster and economic plunder they had seen in neighboring mining communities, so they decided to organize. They demanded that the Progreso VII Derivada mining megaproject, currently run by the US-based mining company Kappes, Cassiday & Associates (KCA), leave their community.\r\n\r\nIn March of 2012 community members blocked the entrance to the mine. One of the longest-runningand most successfulactions in Guatemalas rich history of resistance to mining on indigenous and mestiza land had begun. For four years, women, men, and children have organized in shifts to prevent gold mining operations on their lands. Local activists put their lives on the line, with women lying down in the road to block the entry of mining machinery. Theyve been met with violent eviction by the police, smear campaigns, and constant harassment.\r\n\r\nAna, now 23, is a young woman with a strong commitment. These projects are a time bomb for the communities, she explains. Were trying to stop the destruction and pollution of the environment. The La Puya Resistance won a huge battle in February 2016 when the countrys Constitutional Court upheld an earlier decision by the Supreme Court of Justice to suspend mining operations at Progreso VII. The goal now is to definitively rescind the operating license. To definitively close the mine would be a great achievement for us and for Guatemala, Ana affirms. Its part of saving mother nature.\r\n\r\nEven with this victory, Ana realizes that she has a lifetime of struggle ahead. According to a complaint filed by La Puya, despite the permit suspension the company continues to secretly take out gold ore. Also, if the mine is closed, Ana is concerned the media will stop covering the story, and the movement will be more vulnerable without the international spotlight that she believes has saved them from worse repression in the past.\r\n\r\nPeople in the movement understand that their resistance at La Puya is one step down a long road. But that step has already changed lives. Ana is now attending law school. As a lawyer, I can help the movement, and not only in the case of La Puya. Because this is not a fight that is going to end any time soon. There are more than 20 mining projects planned for the region.\r\n	2016-09-08 20:08:49.879194	\N	f	t	1	https://www.globalfundforwomen.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/ana_thumbnail.png	\N
1109	Maria	Lee	1986	Today	https://mcruzlee.nyc/	1072	Maria Cruz Lee is a leader when it comes to fighting for the rights of both documented and undocumented immigrants across the country. \r\n\r\nBorn in the Philippines, she aims to continually connect, support and celebrate immigrants in all her efforts. She has truly inspired me to take a harder look at the issues impacting our immigrant populations and I admire her for taking on so many tasks at such a young age to advance the mission of helping immigrants, both from the Philippines and abroad. \r\n\r\nShe is a Board Member of the Queens-based non-profit, Pilipino American Unity for Progress (UniPro) which seeks to transform Pilipino students & young professionals into community leaders through its various programs that incorporate professional development, history and policy through the lens of the Pilipino experience. Maria is also a Board Member of the newly formed Filipino American Democratic Club of NY, the first-ever political club that organizes and leads the Filipino American electorate in New York City and New York State. \r\n\r\nBut Maria's efforts go beyond just the Filipino community. She served as Special Assistant to former Commissioner Fatima Shama at the New York City Mayors Office of Immigrant Affairs (MOIA) during the Bloomberg administration. She had joined MOIA as its first social media intern in 2010, created and implemented the agencys social media strategy on multiple campaigns. This is where I met her. We were competing against one another for a social media award and she won. I examined her campaigns and was truly impressed by her work. Soon after, we began collaborating on initiatives to benefit immigrant communities in New York City.  \r\n\r\nI was sad when she left the City, but saw her work spread nationally. Maria was responsible for directing the implementation of Define Americans engagement initiatives and development of new programs. Every few weeks, it seemed like she was traveling the country to spread the mission of Define American. And although she no longer works there, she continues her work to bring the stories of our immigrant populations to the forefront.  \r\n\r\nMaria's work and tireless efforts to bring awareness to the problems faced by our immigrant population are an inspiration today when so many people are looking to target undocumented immigrants and keep them out of our country. In a country built by immigrants, Maria Cruz Lee gives me faith that we can all unite together and eliminate the barriers or "walls" that limit our understanding of all immigrants.  \r\n\r\nShe deserves to be honored and respected for her work in such a short amount of time.  I look forward to seeing what more she will accomplish in the years ahead.  \r\n\r\n	2016-08-31 20:19:59.844721	\N	f	t	1	https://s3.amazonaws.com/everipedia-storage/ProfilePics/6666600438926610262.PNG	\N
1124	Judith 	Lasch	1939	2004		\N	Judith Lasch was a television pioneer. At the dawn of cable TV in the 1980's, Judith recognized  that this new media could serve as a vibrant educational tool and also provide access for underserved voices.  While others raced to be part of "MTV" and other pop movements, Judith began producing "Focus On New York," a weekly show dedicated to giving community members, leaders, and businesses access to TV messaging that had previously only been available to corporate media buyers.  Over the next few years, Judith partnered with her three daughters to create Lasch Media and produce programming involving more global concepts, such as their roundtable series "World Affairs - Women's Perspectives" - a ground-breaking concept at the time. When Lasch Media worked to acquire sponsorship for the programming, it was told that "no audience would respect" or "want to hear news from women commentators."  Judith Lasch, accompanied by her production company powered by women, was a visionary leader at the forefront of public access to televised media.  Judith Lasch, widowed at 23 while pregnant with twins and a 2-yr old toddler, never forgot the value of education as a tool for those without access - and the value of the media as a tool for delivering educational access.  This is an issue and an approach that remains as vital today.	2016-09-04 18:38:31.388987	\N	f	t	1	http://ak-cache.legacy.com/legacy/images/Cobrands/Batesville/photos/Judith-Magee-Lasch-dead-98fd33b8-6d7c-4d2e-8bdf-fca0cb327f80.jpgx?w=80&h=80&option=0&v=0x0000000028e33bc8	\N
