1210	Michelle	Kwan	1980		http://www.fitness.gov/meet-our-team/michelle-kwan/	1155	Michelle Kwan (born July 7, 1980) member of the President's Council on Fitness, Sports & Nutrition, is the most decorated figure skater in U.S. history. No American man or woman has won more world titles (5), national titles (9), or Olympic medals (2). She has earned numerous awards and honors, including: 2003 U.S. Olympic Committee SportsWoman of the Year, 2001 Sullivan Award as the top amateur athlete in America, and 1998 Sportswoman of the Year by the Women's Sports Foundation. The daughter of Hong Kong immigrants, Kwan was born in California and began skating when she was five, entering and winning her first figure skating competition a year later. She finished eighth in the 1994 World Championships at the age of 13, earning a spot as an alternate for the 1994 Olympic Games where she captured the world title in 1996, 1998, 2000, 2001 and 2003. Kwan won a silver medal at the Nagano Olympics in 1998 and a bronze at the Salt Lake City Olympics in 2002. In 2006 she enrolled at the University of Denver to complete her undergraduate degree, also beginning her diplomatic work around this time when the U.S. State Department named her a public advocacy envoy, which involved traveling to different countries to share her experiences with others. In 2009 she enrolled at Tufts University to pursue a Masters in Law and Diplomacy and served as a TV correspondent for ABC for the 2010 Winter Olympics. After completing her degree, Kwan continued to pursue a career in diplomacy. Kwan currently serves as a Public Diplomacy Envoy for the U.S. State Department, on the Board of Directors of Special Olympics International, and the State Departments Council to Empower Women and Girls Through Sports. She is presently employed by the State Department as a senior adviser for public diplomacy and public affairs. Source: (1) President's Council on Fitness, Sports & Nutrition, (2) Washington Post	2016-12-05 18:48:59.562982	\N	f	t	1	https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/originals/bb/e8/67/bbe8673e189e813cdc4c5743e0ac88a6.jpg	\N
1211	Debra	Messing	1968		http://www.psi.org/partnership/ambassadors/debra-messing/	1156	Debra Messing (born August 15, 1968) is an American actress and Global Health Ambassador for PSI. She is known for her many television roles, most notably her eight-year run playing Grace Adler on the NBC sitcom Will & Grace. Following her graduation from New York University's Tisch School of the Arts, Messing had short-lived tenures on the Fox sitcom Ned & Stacey and the ABC sci-fi Prey but rose to prominence in her role as interior designer Grace Adler on the NBC sitcom Will & Grace, earning both commercial and critical success throughout the series' run.  As an Ambassador. In 2009 and 2012, Debra traveled with PSI to Zimbabwe and Zambia, respectively, as PSIs YouthAIDS ambassador, to highlight the countries as one of the few success stories in terms of decline in HIV prevalence and increase in prevention practices in the area. Source (1) PSI (2) Wikepedia	2016-12-05 18:50:46.823088	\N	f	t	1	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/Debra_Messing_July_13_2014_cropped_and_lighting_corrected.jpg/220px-Debra_Messing_July_13_2014_cropped_and_lighting_corrected.jpg	\N
1212	Elizabeth 	Glaser	1947	1994	http://jwa.org/sites/jwa.org/files/styles/default_full/public/mediaobjects/elizabeth_glasersm.jpg?itok=V1rzHzJF	1157	Elizabeth Glaser (1947-1944) Elizabeth Glasers fight to save her HIV-positive children led to her creation of the Pediatric AIDS Foundation to save children worldwide from the devastation of AIDS. A schoolteacher in West Hollywood, Glaser became infected with HIV in 1981 due to a blood transfusion during childbirth and passed the disease to her daughter Ariel through breast milk and to her son Jake in utero. The family discovered what had happened in 1985, after Ariel fell ill. Glaser fought to raise awareness of pediatric AIDS and, once the FDA approved AZT as an effective AIDS medication, pushed hard to extend availability of the drug to children. Unfortunately, her efforts were too late to save Ariel, who died in 1988. That year, Glaser founded the Pediatric AIDS Association, which has raised millions for research, prevention, and treatment. The Pediatric AIDS Foundation had one critical mission: to bring hope to children with HIV and AIDS. Glaser made her first trip to Washington in 1988, when she met with President and Mrs. Reagan, representatives at NIH, and members of Congress. In 1989, the Foundation held its first fundraiser and awarded its first grant for research on the immune dysfunctions in children living with HIV. Glasers advocacy led to profiles on 60 Minutes and in People magazine. In 1992, Glaser spoke out at the Democratic National Convention, criticizing the governments failure to address the AIDS crisis. Her 1991 book, In the Absence of Angels, was praised for its honest discussion of the devastation of losing a child and the difficulties of mourning in the media spotlight. Glaser lost her own battle with AIDS in 1994, and to honor her legacy, the Pediatric AIDS Foundation was renamed the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation (EGPAF). Under this name, EGPAF has become the leading global nonprofit organization dedicated to preventing pediatric HIV infection and eliminating pediatric AIDS through research, advocacy, and prevention and treatment programs. Glasers legacy lives on in her son, Jake, who is now a healthy young adult. Source: (1) Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric Aids Foundation (2) Jewish Women's Archive	2016-12-05 18:54:51.058319	\N	f	t	1	http://b.3cdn.net/glaser/33041cabc5e6e050ef_dlcm6n7qz.jpg	\N
1213	Angelina	Jolie	1975		http://time.com/2865972/angelina-jolie-humanitarian/	1158	Angelina Jolie (born June 4, 1975) is an American actress and humanitarian. Jolie began acting at a young age, studying at the Lee Strasberg Theater Institute while in her early teens. In the 1990s,  Jolie became a popular actress, winning a best actress Golden Globe for her performance in the 1998 television film Gia based on the short, tragic life of model Gia Marie Carangi. Another great dramatic role in Girl, Interrupted (1999) brought Jolie her first Academy Award for best supporting actress. Made a Goodwill Ambassador for the UN Refugee Agency in 2001, Jolie has been a tireless advocate for refugees around the world, making headlines for her work to obtain aid for refugees in Cambodia, Darfur and Jordan, to name just a few.In 2005, Jolie received the Global Humanitarian Action Award from the United Nations Association of the USA for her activism on behalf of refugee rights. In the years since, her work on behalf of the homeless and dispossessed has taken her to more than 30 countries   including a few war zones  and to Washington, D.C., where she has pushed for legislation to assist refugees in troubled regions around the world. She has continued to draw attention to global issues. Source (1) Bio.com (2) Time.	2016-12-05 19:39:37.64867	\N	f	t	1	http://i.huffpost.com/gadgets/slideshows/364692/slide_364692_4135590_free.jpg	\N
1214	Ada Mara	Isasi-Daz			https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/07/nyregion/ISASI-DIAZ-obit/ISASI-DIAZ-obit-popup.jpg	1159	Dr Ada Mara Isasi-Daz (1943-2012) was a Cuban-born professor emerita of ethics and theology at Drew University in Madison, New Jersey. As a Hispanic theologian, she was widely known in North and South America as the chief theorist behind Mujerista theology  she published a book of the same name in 1996  which extols the role of Hispanic women, especially the poor, in personifying Christian faith in the everyday struggles of life. Her identity as a liberationist theologian was shaped very early on in her Catholic upbringing in Cuba, where her deep concern for the poor and the oppressed was nourished. Isasi-Daz would have become a Roman Catholic priest, she told friends, if not for the churchs ban on ordaining women. Instead, she became a dissident theologian who spoke for those she considered the neglected spiritual core of the churchs membership: Hispanic women like herself. When learning of her death in 2012, Drew University mourned her passing but celebrated "her amazing and rich legacy of a pioneeering theologian". Source: (1) New York Times (2) Drew University (3) Wikepedia	2016-12-05 19:42:09.121288	\N	f	t	1	https://users.drew.edu/aisasidi/photo1.jpg	\N
